4 STATE OF MAINE
5 SENATE
6 132ND LEGISLATURE
7 FIRST SPECIAL SESSION
8 SENATE AMENDMENT “ ” to H.P. 1040, L.D. 1582, “An Act to Clarify the
9 Prohibition on the Sale of Beverages in Plastic Containers”
10 Amend the bill by striking out everything after the enacting clause and inserting the
11 following:
12 'Sec. 1. 38 MRSA §3102, sub-§2, as amended by PL 2017, c. 10, §1, is further
13 amended to read:
14 2. Beverage container. "Beverage container" means a bottle, can, jar or other
15 container made of glass, metal or plastic that has been sealed by a manufacturer and at the
16 time of sale contains 4 liters or less of a beverage. "Beverage container" does not include
17 a container composed, in whole or in part, of aluminum and plastic or aluminum and paper
18 in combination as long as the aluminum content represents 10% or less of the unfilled
19 container weight, the container materials represent 5% or less of the total weight of the
20 container and its contents and the container is filled with a nonalcoholic beverage.
21 "Beverage container" does not include a container composed of cardboard in combination
22 with a plastic liner. "Beverage container" does not include a plastic can as described in
23 section 3110, subsection 2.
24 Sec. 2. 38 MRSA §3110, sub-§2, as enacted by PL 2015, c. 166, §14, is amended
25 to read:
26 2. Plastic cans. In a container composed of one or more plastics if the basic structure
27 of the container, exclusive of the closure device, also includes aluminum or steel, unless
28 the container contains 200 milliliters or less of an alcoholic beverage at the time of sale.'
29 Amend the bill by relettering or renumbering any nonconsecutive Part letter or section
30 number to read consecutively.
31 SUMMARY
3322 This amendment replaces the bill. It exempts plastic cans that contain 200 milliliters or
3333 less of an alcoholic beverage from the prohibition on selling or offering for sale beverages
